@ThinkingandTinkering I had watched it but don't think that tests on a cool panel in Winter are giving the full picture, what I am trying to say is that yes you will get an increase, but as the panel temperature rises then the actual gain is much less than you might think,
If this was incorporated into commercial products with some of the gain going to cool the panel, and an overall increase of around 10% then it would be a benefit, but then maintenance/replacement of parts, extra cleaning costs, etc. would negate most of the added value, It's probably more cost effective to put up an extra few panels instead,

If I've learnt anything about solar then my main takeaway would be the 'Law of diminishing returns'

@ThinkingandTinkering that's really interesting.
I wonder if these could increase power if reflecting light back towards a horizontal panel on a camper van roof in winter?
Leave the panel flat, set a reflector at maybe just off vertical, facing the sun?
